ğŸŸ© Bipartite Graph â€” DFS & BFS Implementation
 link: https://leetcode.com/problems/is-graph-bipartite/
ğŸ”¹ Concept

A graph is Bipartite if you can color all its vertices using only two colors (say 0 and 1) such that no two adjacent vertices have the same color.

That means if we divide all vertices into two disjoint sets A and B,
every edge connects a vertex in A to a vertex in B â€” not within the same set.

ğŸ”¹ Examples
âœ… Example 1 (Bipartite)
0 â€” 1
|    |
3 â€” 2


You can color:
0,2 -> color 0 and 1,3 -> color 1.
No adjacent nodes share a color â†’ Bipartite âœ…

âŒ Example 2 (Not Bipartite)
0 â€” 1 â€” 2 â€” 0


This is a cycle of odd length (3) â†’ cannot be colored with 2 colors â†’ Not Bipartite âŒ

ğŸ”¹ Key Property

A graph is Bipartite â‡” it has no odd-length cycle.

ğŸ”¹ Applications

Graph coloring problems

Matching problems in bipartite graphs

Network flow algorithms

Checking validity in scheduling and partition problems

ğŸ§  Intuition

We try to color the graph alternately while traversing:

Start with any node and color it 0.

Color all its neighbors 1.

Then, color their neighbors 0, and so on.

If, during traversal, any adjacent node already has the same color,
it means thereâ€™s a conflict (odd cycle) â†’ Not Bipartite.

ğŸ”¹ Approach 1: DFS Traversal
âœ… Algorithm Steps

Initialize a color[] array with -1 for all vertices (uncolored).

For each vertex i (in case of multiple components):

If uncolored, start a DFS with color 0.

In the DFS function:

Assign the current color to the node.

Traverse all its neighbors:

If neighbor is uncolored, assign opposite color and call DFS recursively.

If neighbor is already colored with the same color, return false.

If DFS for all components returns true â†’ graph is Bipartite.

ğŸ’» DFS Code (C++)
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class Solution {
private: 
    bool dfs(int node, int col, int color[], vector<int> adj[]) {
        color[node] = col; 
        
        for(auto it : adj[node]) {
            if(color[it] == -1) {
                if(dfs(it, !col, color, adj) == false)
                    return false;
            }
            else if(color[it] == col)
                return false;
        }
        return true;
    }

public:
	bool isBipartite(int V, vector<int> adj[]) {
	    int color[V];
	    for(int i = 0; i < V; i++)
	        color[i] = -1; 
	    
	    for(int i = 0; i < V; i++) {
	        if(color[i] == -1) {
	            if(dfs(i, 0, color, adj) == false)
	                return false;
	        }
	    }
	    return true;
	}
};

âš™ï¸ Time Complexity

O(V + 2E) â†’ 2E because every edge is visited twice.

V for looping through all nodes.

ğŸ§® Space Complexity

O(V) for:

color[] array

Recursion stack

Adjacency list (implicit)

ğŸ”¹ Approach 2: BFS Traversal
âœ… Algorithm Steps

Initialize color[] = -1.

For each uncolored node:

Assign color 0.

Perform BFS:

For each node popped from queue:

For each neighbor:

If uncolored â†’ assign opposite color and push in queue.

If colored same as current â†’ return false.

If all nodes processed successfully â†’ Bipartite.

ğŸ’» BFS Code (C++)
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class Solution {
public:
	bool isBipartite(int V, vector<int> adj[]) {
	    vector<int> color(V, -1);
	    
	    for(int start = 0; start < V; start++) {
	        if(color[start] == -1) {
	            queue<int> q;
	            q.push(start);
	            color[start] = 0;
	            
	            while(!q.empty()) {
	                int node = q.front(); q.pop();
	                
	                for(auto it : adj[node]) {
	                    if(color[it] == -1) {
	                        color[it] = !color[node];
	                        q.push(it);
	                    }
	                    else if(color[it] == color[node]) {
	                        return false;
	                    }
	                }
	            }
	        }
	    }
	    return true;
	}
};

âš™ï¸ Time Complexity

O(V + 2E)
Every vertex and edge is traversed once.

ğŸ§® Space Complexity

O(V) for color array and queue.

ğŸ”¹ DFS vs BFS Comparison
Feature	DFS	BFS
Traversal Type	Depth First (Recursive)	Level-wise (Iterative)
Data Structure	Recursion Stack	Queue
Best For	Recursive implementation	Easier to visualize level coloring
Space Used	Stack space + color[]	Queue + color[]
Performance	Same Time Complexity	Same Time Complexity

Both give same result and are interchangeable.

ğŸŸ© Edge Cases

âœ… Disconnected Graph â†’ handle using loop for all nodes
âœ… Single Node â†’ always Bipartite
âœ… No edges â†’ always Bipartite
âŒ Graph with Odd Cycle â†’ Not Bipartite

ğŸ”¹ Example Dry Run (DFS)

Graph:

0 -- 1 -- 2
|         |
-----------


Adjacency list:

0 -> 1, 2
1 -> 0, 2
2 -> 0, 1


Steps:

Start from 0 â†’ color[0] = 0

Visit 1 â†’ color[1] = 1

Visit 2 from 1 â†’ color[2] = 0
Back to 0, 2 is already 0 â†’ same as 0 â†’ Not Bipartite

ğŸ Final Notes / Summary
Step	BFS/DFS	Purpose
1	Initialize color[] = -1	Track coloring
2	Traverse each unvisited node	Handle disconnected graphs
3	Assign color 0	Starting color
4	Alternate colors	0 â†” 1
5	Check same color adjacency	Detect odd cycle
6	Return result	True â†’ Bipartite, False â†’ Not
âœ… Takeaway

Even cycle or no cycle â†’ Bipartite

Odd cycle â†’ Not Bipartite

DFS or BFS both work â†’ O(V + E) time.
